docs.abstract: Flight instructors and aviation experts were split on whether video games and simulations could prepare someone to operate a real plane.

docs.lead_paragraph: As he flew the stolen 76-seat passenger plane above the Seattle area for nearly an hour on Friday night, Richard B. Russell was asked by an air traffic controller whether he was comfortable “just flying the plane around.”

headline.main: Richard Russell Stole a Plane in Seattle and Crashed It. How’d He Learn to Fly?

docs.abstract: A ground service agent at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport flew a stolen turboprop for just under an hour before eventually crashing 30 miles away. There were no other passengers on board.

docs.abstract: Richard B. Russell, a ground service agent at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, flew a turboprop aircraft for nearly an hour over Puget Sound.
docs.snippet: Richard B. Russell, a ground service agent at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, flew a turboprop aircraft for nearly an hour over Puget Sound.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — The story is as bizarre as it is tragic: An airline worker who had no business being in a cockpit somehow took off from a major airport in a turboprop passenger plane, dipped and soared in the skies above the Seattle area, and then crashed into an island on Puget Sound.

headline.main: Richard Russell, Who Stole Plane Near Seattle, Raises Troubling Security Questions
headline.print_headline: Commandeered Plane Sets Off Security Concerns

byline.original: By Kirk Johnson, Jacey Fortin and Christina Caron

docs.abstract: Corporations are saving cash, cutting costs and refinancing debt to manage the economic fallout of the coronavirus. Restructuring and bankruptcy experts are already getting calls.
docs.snippet: Corporations are saving cash, cutting costs and refinancing debt to manage the economic fallout of the coronavirus. Restructuring and bankruptcy experts are already getting calls.
docs.lead_paragraph: Freedom Mortgage, one of the nation’s largest mortgage lenders, is looking for additional financing as millions of homeowners are expected to stop making mortgage payments. The Cheesecake Factory said this past week it wouldn’t be able to make rent payments on its leases because of lost business. And giant companies from Kraft Heinz to Ford have tapped billions of dollars in credit from banks in preparation for an uncertain future.

headline.main: Scary Times for U.S. Companies Spell Boom for Restructuring Advisers
headline.print_headline: Panic Fuels Rush to Call Restructuring Advisers
